<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="1">
Akysid catfishes of the genus 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:66411714-0B55-4CE6-A98E-12684F9D26E6" class="Actinopterygii" family="Akysidae" genus="Acrochordonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Acrochordonichthys Bleeker 1857:473" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Acrochordonichthys Bleeker</taxonomicName>
, 1858, inhabit the bottom of rivers throughout Southeast Asia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="1">They have a highly rugose skin with tubercles arranged in longitudinal rows along the side of the body, a long, low adipose fin, and an emarginate caudal fin.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="1">Until the recent revision by Ng &amp; Ng (2001), the genus has been poorly studied, mainly due to difficulty in distinguishing the species and lack of sufficient comparative material.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
